[2] International donations
- Sat 6 Oct 2018. Russia allocates over USD 60 million to fight Ebola in Africa
[TASS Russian News Agency, abridged, edited]
<tass.com/society/1024816>

Russia has allocated more than USD 60 million to fight Ebola in Western Africa, Russian Presidential Special Representative for the Middle East and Africa Mikhail Bogdanov said in his address to a session of the World Public Forum - Dialogue of Civilizations.

Currently, Moscow is actively assisting Africans in healthcare and medicine, he said.

"Russia has donated a total of USD 100 million to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria," said Bogdanov, who is also a deputy foreign minister.

"We continue providing assistance in the fight against the Ebola virus disease. For the purpose, Russia has allocated more than USD 60 million to eradicate this dangerous disease in Western Africa," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

- Fri 5 Oct 2018. UK gives Uganda GBP 5.1 million [about USD 6.7] to fight Ebola
[New Vision, Uganda, abridged, edited]
https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1487062/uk-uganda-51m-pounds-fight-ebola
[Byline: Cecilia Okoth]

The United Kingdom government has provided Uganda with funds amounting to GBP 5.1 million pounds (about UGX 25 billion) meant to fight Ebola.

While visiting the Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) on Fri 5 Oct 2018, UK's Minister for Africa Harriett Baldwin announced additional funds to be channeled towards tackling Ebola.

"Most topical at the moment is the outbreak of Ebola. The work that you are doing here is very important in terms of the quick turnaround of the diagnosis and finding out where the spread of the virus is happening," Baldwin stated.

"As you know, there is now an experimental vaccine for Ebola that has been deployed for the 1st time this year [2018] and the kind of work that is happening here is saving lives every day," she said.

Due to the prevailing outbreak of Ebola in DRC, Uganda has intensified surveillance and preparedness response in the high risk districts. Thermo scanners have been installed at Entebbe International Airport to screen all passengers coming in from DRC.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The UK and Russian governments are to be commended for these financial commitments to combat Ebola in Africa. However, TASS reports that Russia's allocation is for Western Africa, so it is not clear what portion if any of those funds will go to help fight the current outbreak in the DRC, which is generally considered part of Central Africa.

The UK donation is not for the DRC, but for neighboring Uganda, a former British colony. Last week WHO Director-General Dr Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus reported to the UN Security Council [3 Oct 2018] that "To date, we have pledges for USD 8 million out of a request for USD 33 million for this critical work." (see Ebola update (105) 20181005.6072036).

In the original DRC MOH National Response Plan that was issued only a few weeks after the current North Kivu outbreak was declared, the total budget was estimated at about USD 44 million, based on certain key assumptions (for details, see Ebola update (75) 20180823.5981519). Financial figures are as important as epidemiological numbers in an international public-private Ebola outbreak response, so it would be very informative to have an agency or organization track the various financial commitments and uses thereof on a publicly available website. - Mod.LXL]

