[3] Novel PPE suit
Date: Sat 6 Oct 2018
Source: American Journal of Infection Control [edited]
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ajic.2018.08.014


ref: Garibaldi BT, Ruparelia C, Shaw-Saliba K, et al. A novel personal protective equipment coverall was rated higher than standard Ebola virus personal protective equipment in terms of comfort, mobility and perception of safety when tested by health care workers in Liberia and in a United States biocontainment unit. Am J Infect Control. 2018. Available online 6 Oct 2018
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Background
----------
During the 2014-2016 Ebola virus epidemic, more than 500 health care workers (HCWs) died in spite of the use of personal protective equipment (PPE). The Johns Hopkins University Center for Bioengineering Innovation and Design (CBID) and Jhpiego, an international nongovernmental organization affiliate of Johns Hopkins, collaborated to create new PPE to improve the ease of the doffing process.

Methods
-------
HCWs in Liberia and a US biocontainment unit compared standard Médecins Sans Frontières PPE (PPE A) with the new PPE (PPE B). Participants wore each PPE ensemble while performing simulated patient care activities. Range of motion, time to doff, comfort, and perceived risk were measured.

Results
-------
Overall, 100% of participants preferred PPE B over PPE A (P less than .0001); 98.1% of respondents would recommend PPE B for their home clinical unit (P less than .0001). There was a trend towards greater comfort in PPE B. HCWs at both sites felt more at risk in PPE A than PPE B (71.9% vs 25% in Liberia, P less than .0001; 100% vs 40% in the US biocontainment unit, P less than .0001).

Conclusions
-----------
HCWs preferred a new PPE ensemble to the Médecins Sans Frontières' PPE for high-consequence pathogens. Further studies on the safety of this new PPE need to be conducted.

--
Communicated by:
Greg Folkers
NIAID, NIH
<gfolkers@nih.gov>
and
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Although difficult to quantify, at least some of the Ebola infections accidentally acquired by healthcare workers (HCW's) are due to mishaps in the arduous process of doffing contaminated PPE suits. The novel PPE suit described in this article was designed by the Johns Hopkins affiliates above in response to an Ebola Grand Challenge competition sponsored by the USAID and other US governmental agencies during the 2014-2016 West African epidemic to develop innovative approaches for Ebola health care worker activities. In addition to convenient rear pull tabs that promote faster removal, the suit also has a large clear face mask that allow both HCW's and their patients to better see each other. It also comes with a belt-worn battery-powered personal air conditioner unit that blows dry filtered air into the suit, enhancing HCW comfort (although such units may not be feasible or affordable in certain resource-limited regions).

Unfortunately, full access to this article requires a journal subscription. But one can visualize the prototype PPE suit design at
http://files.gereports.com/images/ebola-suit_comparison.png (illustrated diagram comparing features of the traditional versus the new Ebola suits)
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kRab2bGahCE (short video of the suit's features and simplified doffing process). - Mod.LXL]
